# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:07:19
overview:<p>The King Crab was designed in 2741 by Cosara Weaponries at the direct request of General Aleksandr Kerensky for an assault 'Mech capable of crippling or destroying another BattleMech in a single salvo. Filling the role of a devastating close-range combatant, the hundred-ton King Crab earned its fearsome reputation through the raw destructive power of its twin super-heavy autocannons, mounted in distinctive claw-like arm housings that gave the design its name. Though initially envisioned as a potential command vehicle, the King Crab proved less suited to that capacity than expected, a role ultimately filled by the Atlas.</p><p>Production was centered at Cosara facilities on Mars and Northwind under Star League authority, with the design seeing widespread service in the SLDF. The devastation of the Succession Wars reduced the King Crab to near-extinction, but ComStar's secret preservation of the Mars factory ensured the design's survival and eventual return to mass production in the thirty-first century.</p>
capabilities:<p>The King Crab's tactical doctrine is straightforward: close with the enemy and deliver overwhelming firepower. Its primary armament of twin Deathgiver Autocannon/20s represents one of the most destructive weapon pairings ever mounted on a BattleMech, capable of stripping the armor from virtually any opponent in a few devastating salvos. The autocannons are housed within reinforced arm assemblies fitted with simple hand actuators that function as protective cowlings, giving the 'Mech its distinctive crab-like silhouette and the appearance of pincers opening and closing in combat. A Simpson-15 LRM launcher and Exostar large laser provide secondary fire support at longer ranges, ensuring the King Crab is not entirely helpless during its approach to engagement range.</p><p>Sixteen tons of Aldis X ferro-fibrous armor provide solid, evenly distributed protection across the chassis, with CASE safeguarding the ammunition stores from catastrophic detonation. The arms represent a notable vulnerability, however, as an internal hit to either limb can knock an autocannon out of the fight entirely. The King Crab's most significant limitation is its dependence on ammunition; each autocannon draws from a mere five-round magazine, giving pilots limited sustained firepower before running dry. Combined with a modest top speed of 54 kilometers per hour and a well-earned reputation as a maintenance-intensive design, the King Crab demands careful tactical employment and reliable logistics to realize its devastating potential.</p>
deployment:<p>Introduced in 3143 as a factory-produced version of a successful field modification, this variant replaces the standard KGC-009's autocannons and missile launchers with Clan-specification Hyper-Assault Gauss Rifles, dramatically increasing ranged firepower. The medium lasers give way to Clan-grade ER small lasers, while Clan plasma rifles replace the Inner Sphere models for improved performance. Produced by StarCorps Industries at Loburg, this hybrid design demonstrates the increasing availability of Clan technology to Inner Sphere manufacturers during the Dark Age period, offering Lyran forces a significant upgrade in striking power while retaining the KGC-009's robust chassis and heavy armor protection.</p>
history:<p>The King Crab's origins trace to 2741, when General Aleksandr Kerensky personally commissioned Cosara Weaponries to design an assault 'Mech of unmatched destructive power. The resulting design exceeded expectations, and production commenced at Cosara's facilities on Mars and Northwind. The King Crab served with distinction in the SLDF throughout the final decades of the Star League, though it never displaced the Atlas as the preferred command vehicle for senior officers. When the Amaris Civil War erupted in 2767, Republican forces destroyed the Mars factory, leaving only the Northwind facility operational.</p><p>The Exodus of 2784 dealt the King Crab a severe blow, as General Kerensky's departing forces took the vast majority of existing King Crabs with them, including the entire production run of the prototype KGC-010. The Northwind factory's destruction in 2786, an early casualty of the First Succession War, effectively ended new production in the Inner Sphere. The King Crab's relatively simple construction meant surviving examples were easier to maintain than many Star League-era designs, but attrition took its toll. By the close of the Third Succession War, only a handful remained in active service with the Great Houses, each one a prized and jealously guarded asset.</p><p>ComStar's seizure of Terra through Operation Silver Shield proved critical to the King Crab's survival. The order's technicians repaired and mothballed the damaged Mars factory, secretly stockpiling King Crabs for future use. By the early thirty-first century, ComStar contracted Cosara Weaponries to quietly resume production to replenish their aging reserves, equipping the Com Guards with refurbished and newly built King Crabs. The looming threat of the Clan Invasion spurred the development of the KGC-001 "Clanbuster" variant in 3052, which proved so successful at the Battle of Tukayyid that ComStar authorized general market sales from both the Mars and Northwind plants, with Cosara receiving a share of profits.</p><p>The Word of Blake's conquest of Terra and subsequent seizure of the Northwind factory in 3069 upended King Crab production once again. The Blakists retooled the Northwind line to produce their own variants, including the jump-capable KGC-008 for Protectorate forces. ComStar responded with an uncharacteristically bold move, dispatching a mercenary espionage team to infiltrate the Northwind facility and steal the new design specifications. These plans were then offered to StarCorps Industries, who eagerly began producing the KGC-007 at their Son Hoa plant for ComStar, the Lyran Alliance, and the Federated Suns alike.</p><p>The post-Jihad era saw continued evolution of the King Crab. StarCorps relocated their production line from Son Hoa to Loburg in the late 3090s, introducing the modernized KGC-009 in 3104 to meet the demands of the Lyran Commonwealth Armed Forces. The design proved popular with senior Lyran officers despite its continued ammunition dependency. Cosara Weaponries eventually returned the Mars facility to active production under Republic of the Sphere oversight, developing the KGC-011 with its revolutionary XXL engine for dramatically improved battlefield mobility. By the ilClan era, the King Crab remained a respected and feared assault platform, its production split between Cosara's historic Mars facility and StarCorps' Loburg plant, ensuring the design's continued presence on battlefields across the Inner Sphere.</p>
